{{ZenBuddhism}}
The '''Hongzhou school''' ({{zh|c=洪州宗|p=Hóngzhōu Zōng}}) was a [[Chinese Chán|Chinese school of Chán]] of the [[Tang period]], which started with [[Mazu Daoyi]] (709–788). It became the archetypal expression of [[Zen]] during the [[Song Dynasty]].

==History==
[[File:RinzaiGigen.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Rinzai]]

The [[An Lu-shan Rebellion]] (755-763) led to a loss of control by the Tang dynasty, which changed the position of Chan. Metropolitan Chan began to lose its status, while...
{{quote|...other schools were arising in outlying areas controlled by warlords. These are the forerunners of the Chan we know today. Their origins are obscure; the power of Shen-hui's preaching is shown by the fact that they all trace themselves to Hui-neng.{{sfn|Yampolski|2003-A|p=11}}}}

===Mazu Daoyi===
Traditionally, Mazu Daoyi (709–788) is depicted as a successor in the lineage of [[Hui-neng]], since his teacher [[Nanyue Huairang]] is regarded as a student and successor of Huineng. This connection between Hui-neng and Nanyue Huairang is doubtful, being the product of later rewritings of Chán-history to place Mazu in the traditional lineages.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=82}}

Mazu settled at Kung-kung Mountain by Nankang, southern Kiangsi province,{{sfn|Chang|1971|p=148-149, 177 }} where he founded a monastery and gathered scores of disciples.{{sfn|Chang|1971|p=152}}

===Baizhang Huaihai===
Baizhang Huaihai (Pai-chang)(720–814) was the dharma heir of Mazu. He is usually said to have established an early set of rules for Chan monastics, the ''Pure Rules of Baizhang'' ({{zh|c=百丈清規 |p=Bǎizhàng qīngguī |w=Pai-chang ch'ing-kuei}}).,{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A|p=170}} but there is no historical evidence that this text ever existed.{{sfn|Poceski|2010|p=19}} Some version of the old Buddhist Vinaya code, modified to some extent for the Chinese situation, was practiced in Dazhi Shousheng Chan-si (Ta-chih shou-sheng ch'an-ssu; Jp. Daichijusho-zenji), founded by Baizhang.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} This monastery contained a monks hall for meditation and sleeping, an innovation which became typical for Chán:
{{quote|During periods of ascetic practice the monks would sleep on the same straw mat on which they sat in meditation and on which, according to defined ritual, they took their meals. Both the lifestyle Pai-chang spelled out as well as the architectural form of his monastery became models for later Zen monasteries".{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A|p=171}}}}

===Huangbo Xiyun===
Very little is known of Huangbo Xiyun (died 850), who was a dharma heir of Baizhang Huaihai. He started his monastic career at Mount Huang-po. In 842 he took up residence at Lung-hsing Monastery ath the invitation of P'ei-hsiu (787 or 797–860). P'ei-hsiu was a lay-student of [[Guifeng Zongmi]],{{sfn|Wright|Year unknown}} fifth-generation heir of the Ho-tse line of the Southern school of [[Shenhui]], and a great scholar. Zongmi was...
{{quote|...critical of the Hung-chou style. For him, this excessively rural school of Buddhism lacked the comprehensive vision that he found in Ho-tse Zen and in the Hua-yen philosophical school of Buddhism.{{sfn|Wright|Year unknown}}}}
Péi-hsiu, however, became interested, and in 842 invited huangbo to the Lung-hsing Monastery.{{sfn|Wright|Year unknown}}

===Linji Yìxuán===
{{main|Linji Yixuan}}
Linji Yìxuán ((died 866 CE)) became the archetypal representant of Chán, as expressed in his recorded sayings. He was a student of Huangbo, who also figures in the ''Recorded sayings of Linj''. According to these records, Linji attained [[kensho]] while discussing Huángbò's teaching with the reclusive monk Dàyú (大愚). Linji then returned to Huángbò to continue his training. In 851 CE, Linji moved to the Linji temple in [[Hebei]], where he took his name, which also became the name for the lineage of his form of Chán Buddhism.

==Teachings==
The Hongzhou school developed "shock techniques such as shouting, beating, and using irrational retorts to startle their students into realization".{{sfn|Kasulis|2003|pp=28–29}}{{sfn|Chang|1967}} Some of these are common today, while others are found mostly in anecdotes. It is common in many Chán traditions today for Chán teachers to have a stick with them during formal ceremonies which is a symbol of authority and which can be also used to strike on the table during a talk.

A well-known story depicts Mazu practicing dhyana, but being chided by his teacher [[Nanyue Huairang]], comparing seated meditation with polishing a tile.{{sfn|Faure|1997|p=73}} According to Faure, the criticism is not about dhyana as such, but 
{{quote|... the idea of "becoming a Buddha" by means of any practice, lowered to the standing of a "means" to achieve an "end".{{sfn|Faure|1997|p=73}}}}

The criticism of seated dhyana reflects a change in the role and position of monks in Tang society, who "undertook only pious works, reciting sacred texts and remaining seated in ''dhyana''".{{sfn|Faure|1997|p=74}} Nevertheless, seated dhyana remained an important part of the Chán tradition, also due to the influence of Guifeng Zongmi, who tried to balance dhyana and insight.{{sfn|Faure|1997|p=74}}

==Texts==
From the "question-and-answer format that had been developed as a means of conveying Buddhist teachings" developed the "yü-lü" genre,{{sfn|Chappell|1993|p=192}} the recorded sayings of the masters, and the encounter dialogues. The best-known example is the "[[Linji Yixuan#External links|Lin-ji yü-lü]]".<ref group=web>[http://info.stiltij.nl/publiek/meditatie/leraren/_historisch/linji-sasaki.pdf Translation of the Lin-ji yü-lü by Fuller-Sasaki]</ref> It is part of the ''Ssu-chia yü lu'' (Jp. Shike Goruku, ''The Collection of the Four Houses''), which contains the recorded sayings of [[Mazu Daoyi]], [[Baizhang Huaihai]], [[Huangbo Xiyun]] and [[Linji Yixuan]].{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A|p=179}}

These recorded sayings are not verbatim recordings of the sayings of the masters, but well-edited texts, written down up to 160 years after the supposed sayings and meetings.{{sfn|Welter|Year unknown}}

==Influence==
Mazu is perhaps the most influential teaching master in the formation of Chán Buddhism in China.{{sfn|Schuhmacher and Woerner (editors)|1991|p=141}} When Chán became the dominant school of Buddhism during the [[Song Dynasty]], in retrospect the later [[Tang Dynasty]] and Mazu's Hongzhou school became regarded as the "golden age" of Chan.{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=18-21}}

The shock techniques became part of the traditional and still popular image of Chan masters displaying irrational and strange behaviour to aid their students.{{sfn|McRae|2003}}{{sfn|Heine|2008}} Part of this image was due to later misinterpretations and translation errors, such as the loud belly shout known as ''katsu''. In Chinese "katsu" means "to shout", which has traditionally been translated as "yelled 'katsu'" - which should mean "yelled a yell"<ref group=web>See [http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/Philosophical/Liberating_Language.html James D. Sellmann & Hans Julius Schneider (2003), ''Liberating Language in Linji and Wittgenstein''. Asian Philosophy, Vol. 13, Nos. 2/3, 2003. Notes 26 and 41]</ref>

The stories about the Hongzhou school are part of the Traditional Zen Narrative which developed in China during the Tang Dynasty and the beginning of the Song Dynasty, from the 7th to 11th century. It became dominant during the Song Dynasty, when Chán was the dominant form of Buddhism in China, due to support from the Emperial Court.{{sfn|McRae|2003}}

This period is seen as the "golden age" of Chan, a "romantic coloring"{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=19}} discarded by McRae:
{{quote|...what is being referred to is not some collection of activities and events that actually happened in the 8th through 10th centuries, but instead the retrospective re-creation of those activities and events, the imagined identities of the magical figures of the Tang, within the minds of Song dynasty Chan devotees{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=19}}[...] This retrospective quality pervades the Chan tradition. Time and again we find we are dealing, not with what happened at any given point, but with what people thought happened previously{{sfn|McRae|2003|p=14}}}}

==Criticism==
The Hung-chou school has been criticised for its radical [[subitism]].

[[Guifeng Zongmi]] (圭峰 宗密) (780–841), an influential teacher-scholar and patriarch of both the Chán and the [[Huayan school]] claimed that the Hung-chou tradition believed "everything as altogether true".{{sfn|Gregory|2002|p=236}}

According to Zongmi, the Hung-chou school teaching led to a radical nondualism that believed that all actions, good or bad, are expressing the essential [[Buddha-nature]], but therefore denies the need for spiritual cultivation and moral discipline. This would be a dangerously [[Antinomianism|antinomian]] view as it eliminated all moral distinctions and validated any actions as expressions of the essence of Buddha-nature.

While Zongmi acknowledged that the essence of Buddha-nature and its functioning in the day-to-day reality are but difference aspects of the same reality, he insisted that there is a difference. To avoid the dualism he saw in the Northern Line and the radical [[nondualism]] and antinomianism of the Hung-chou school, Zongmi’s paradigm preserved "an ethically critical duality within a larger ontological unity",{{sfn|Gregory|2002|p=239}} an [[ontology]] which he claimed was lacking in Hung-chou Chan.

